# Cursor Rules — Meal Management App

## Project Context
This is a Hebrew-only (RTL) web application for managing meal delivery to women after childbirth. 
It coordinates cooks (volunteers who prepare meals) and drivers (volunteers who deliver).
Built with Next.js 14 + Supabase + Tailwind CSS, deployed on Vercel.

## Critical Rules

### Language & Direction
- ALL user-facing text must be in Hebrew
- ALL layouts must be RTL (dir="rtl")
- Use Tailwind RTL utilities (rtl:, ltr:) when needed
- HTML lang="he" on all pages
- Font: system Hebrew fonts or Google Fonts with Hebrew support (e.g., Heebo, Rubik)

### Tech Stack — DO NOT deviate
- Next.js 14 with App Router (NOT Pages Router)
- Tailwind CSS for styling (NO other CSS frameworks)
- Supabase for auth, database, and realtime
- TypeScript for all files
- Supabase Phone Auth (OTP) for authentication — NOT email/password

### Code Style
- Use TypeScript strict mode
- Use server components by default, client components only when needed ('use client')
- Use Supabase SSR helpers for server-side auth
- All database calls through Supabase client
- Use Zod for form validation
- Descriptive variable names in English, comments in Hebrew when clarifying business logic

### File Structure
```
/app
  /layout.tsx          — Root layout (RTL, Hebrew font)
  /page.tsx            — Landing / login
  /(auth)
    /login/page.tsx    — Phone OTP login
    /register/page.tsx — Registration with role selection
  /(dashboard)
    /admin/            — Admin pages
    /beneficiary/      — Beneficiary pages  
    /cook/             — Cook pages
    /driver/           — Driver pages
  /api/                — API routes (webhooks for n8n)
/components
  /ui/                 — Reusable UI components
  /forms/              — Form components
  /calendar/           — Calendar/schedule components
/lib
  /supabase.ts         — Supabase client config
  /types.ts            — TypeScript types
  /utils.ts            — Utility functions
  /constants.ts        — App constants (times, defaults)
```

### Database
- Always use Supabase RLS (Row Level Security) policies
- Never expose admin routes to non-admin users
- Validate role on every protected page/API route

### UI/UX Principles
- Mobile-first design (min-width responsive, not max-width)
- Large touch targets (min 44px)
- Clear Hebrew text, no jargon
- Warm, friendly colors
- Maximum 2-3 taps to complete any action
- Loading states on all async operations
- Toast notifications for confirmations
- Empty states with clear call-to-action

### Security
- Supabase RLS on all tables
- Role-based access control middleware
- Phone number validation (Israeli format: 05X-XXXXXXX)
- Rate limiting on OTP requests
- No sensitive data in client-side code

### n8n Integration
- Expose webhook endpoints at /api/webhooks/
- Send structured JSON payloads
- Include: recipient_phone, message_type, message_data
- n8n handles WhatsApp/SMS delivery logic

### When Building New Features
1. Always read PROJECT.md first
2. Create the database migration/table first
3. Add RLS policies
4. Build the API/server logic
5. Build the UI last
6. Test with Hebrew text (not lorem ipsum)

### Common Mistakes to Avoid
- Do NOT use left/right in CSS — use start/end for RTL compatibility
- Do NOT hardcode dates — use date-fns with Hebrew locale
- Do NOT skip loading states
- Do NOT create pages without role protection
- Do NOT use alert() — use toast components
- Do NOT store phone numbers without normalizing (remove dashes, spaces)
